sequences","Analysis of cell-free fetal DNA in maternal blood","Analysis of placental protein biomarkers","Analysis of circulating fetal cells in plasma","Analysis of maternal serum hormones"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENon-invasive prenatal testing works through \u003Cstrong\u003Eanalysis of cell-free fetal DNA in maternal blood\u003C/strong\u003E. This DNA originates from placental cells that naturally break down and release their contents into maternal circulation. Advanced sequencing techniques can analyse this DNA to detect chromosomal abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnalysis of maternal leucocyte DNA sequences\u003C/strong\u003E - Maternal white blood cells contain only maternal DNA, not fetal DNA\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnalysis of circulating fetal cells in plasma\u003C/strong\u003E - While some intact fetal cells can be found in maternal circulation, non-invasive prenatal testing specifically analyses cell-free DNA, not intact cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnalysis of placental protein biomarkers\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes other types of screening tests, not non-invasive prenatal testing\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnalysis of maternal serum hormones\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes older screening tests like first trimester combined screening, not non-invasive prenatal testing\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECell-free fetal DNA typically comprises 10-15% of total cell-free DNA in maternal blood during pregnancy. This proportion is sufficient to allow accurate screening for common chromosomal abnormalities including trisomies 21, 18, and 13.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-invasive prenatal testing analyses cell-free fetal DNA in maternal blood to screen for chromosomal abnormalities.","Cell-free fetal DNA originates from placental trophoblast cells that naturally break down during pregnancy.","Non-invasive prenatal testing can detect common trisomies (21, 18, 13) and sex chromosome abnormalities with high sensitivity."],"references":["Non-invasive prenatal testing. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2017 Sep 18;46:735\u20139."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63396"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17258"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63396"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T20:43:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T20:44:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9948"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77927"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4935","li